-- SOURCING NOTES (nuances the figures alone don't capture — read before relying on a value):
-- [CO] SOURCES: Official source is the Colorado Revised Statutes published by the Colorado General Assembly / Office of Legislative Legal Services (leg.colorado.gov). The leg.colorado.gov site does not expose stable per-section deep-links to statute text; the per-section verbatim text was read from colorado.public.law (an official-text mirror of the CRS) and cross-checked against Justia's CRS reproduction. All quoted values were verified against the actual statutory language.
-- [CO] ENTRY NOTICE DELIBERATELY OMITTED: Colorado has NO general statutory landlord entry-notice requirement. I specifically chased the widely-repeated property-management-blog claim that HB25-1090 created a 24-hour entry-notice rule. That is FALSE conflation — HB25-1090 ("Protections Against Deceptive Pricing Practices," eff. 2026) regulates junk fees, fee markups, and price disclosure; it contains no right-of-entry provision and does not amend CRS 38-12 for entry. The only statutory entry-notice rules in Colorado are narrow/conditional: (a) habitability remedial-action entry requires 24 hours' notice (§ 38-12-503(2)(c)), and (b) bed-bug inspection requires 48 hours' notice (§ 38-12-1004). Because there is no general entry-notice value, entry_notice_hours was omitted rather than invented.
-- [CO] DEPOSIT RETURN nuance: § 38-12-103(1) sets a default of one month (~30 days); the lease may extend that, but the statute caps the outer bound at 60 days. Recorded as a max of 60 (the absolute statutory ceiling). If GAM prefers the default-floor instead, the no-lease-extension default is one month/30 days.
-- [CO] UNIT-TYPE MAPPING — rv_spot: Colorado has NO separate RV-park act. The Mobile Home Park Act (Part 2) EXPLICITLY EXCLUDES recreational vehicles, travel trailers, fifth-wheels, motor homes, park-model/recreational-park trailers, and truck campers from the definition of 'mobile home' (per § 38-12-201.5 / Division of Housing guidance). Therefore long-term RV-spot tenancies are NOT governed by the MHPA; they fall under general residential/contract law plus Title 13 eviction notice — so rv_spot is mapped to the residential act, not the mobile_home_park act.
-- [CO] MOBILE HOME PARK ACT: § 38-12-105 (late fees) and the security-deposit Part 1 sections by their terms apply to both 'tenant' and 'home owner' (mobile-home park residents), so the late-fee floor/cap also governs mobile-home lot rent. The MHPA additionally carries its own tenancy-termination and rent-increase notice regime distinct from the Part 1 residential deposit rules.
-- [CO] COMMERCIAL: Colorado has no dedicated commercial landlord-tenant statute; commercial leases are governed by negotiated lease terms and common-law contract/property principles, with eviction via the Forcible Entry and Detainer statute (Title 13, Art. 40). The residential deposit/late-fee caps in § 38-12-102.5/103/105 do NOT apply to commercial tenancies.
-- [CO] STORAGE: The Self-Service Storage Facility Liens statute (Title 38, Art. 21.5) is a lien/enforcement framework (30-day continuous default before lien enforcement per § 38-21.5-103), not a residential-style deposit/late-fee/notice scheme; none of the six residential provisions map to it.
-- [CO] VALUES ARE CURRENT as of 2026: the § 38-12-102.5 two-month deposit cap (eff. Aug 7, 2023), the § 38-12-105 7-day/greater-of-$50-or-5% late-fee rule, and the § 38-12-103 one-month/60-day deposit return are all in force. Note HB25-1249 (eff. Jan 1, 2026) tightened deposit-withholding grounds (no withholding for pre-existing damage) but did not change the deposit cap, return window, or late-fee numbers.
