-- [AL] Source: Official Alabama Legislature code portal (alison.legislature.state.al.us). The portal renders statute text via JavaScript, so verbatim text was captured from the al.elaws.us official-code mirror and confirmed against the legislature's section URLs (cited above as the canonical official source).
-- [AL] ACTS / SCOPE:
-- [AL] - Chapter 9A (URLTA, § 35-9A-101 et seq.) is Alabama's residential landlord-tenant act. It governs "dwelling units" — apartments and single-family residences. It expressly does NOT apply to commercial, industrial, or agricultural premises, transient hotel/motel occupancy, condo/co-op owner occupancy, or employee-conditional occupancy (§ 35-9A-122).
-- [AL] - MOBILE/MANUFACTURED HOMES: Alabama has NO comprehensive standalone mobile-home-park tenancy act. Rentals of manufactured homes and mobile-home park LOTS fall under Chapter 9A (URLTA). Act 2022-338 added a 60-day no-cause termination notice specifically for mobile-home-lot tenancies (longer than the general 30-day month-to-month rule). Chapter 12A (§ 35-12A-1 et seq.) is narrowly an "Abandoned Manufactured Dwellings" abandonment/disposal procedure, not a tenancy act. mobile_home is therefore mapped to the residential act.
-- [AL] - RV PARKS: Chapter 15, Article 2A (§ 35-15-30 et seq.) covers recreational vehicle parks but treats RV-park occupants as transient "guests," not tenants — it is a guest-removal/law-enforcement-ejection statute (added/amended by HB555/Act 2021, amended 2021), not a deposit/notice tenancy framework. There is no entry-notice, deposit, or month-to-month-vacate provision for RV spots.
-- [AL] - COMMERCIAL: no dedicated commercial-tenancy statute; commercial leases are governed by the lease terms, general property law (Title 35), and common law.
-- [AL] - STORAGE: no residential-style landlord-tenant act applies to self-storage; Alabama self-service storage facilities are governed by a separate lien statute (Self-Service Storage Facility Act), which is outside the scope of these tenancy acts, so storage was not mapped to an act here.
-- [AL] RESIDENTIAL PROVISIONS:
-- [AL] - entry_notice_hours: § 35-9A-303 requires "at least two days' notice" = 48 hours (statute states days, not hours; converted to 48 hours).
-- [AL] - deposit_max_months: § 35-9A-201(a) caps security at one month's periodic rent (with carve-outs for pets, premises changes, and increased-liability risks that may exceed it).
-- [AL] - deposit_return_days: § 35-9A-201(b) — itemized accounting and amount due 60 days after termination + delivery of possession; failure to comply exposes landlord to double the deposit.
-- [AL] - notice_to_vacate_days: § 35-9A-441(b) — 30 days for month-to-month (week-to-week is 7 days under the same section).
-- [AL] OMITTED (statute is genuinely silent — no number invented):
-- [AL] - late_fee_max_pct: Alabama URLTA does NOT cap late fees. No statutory percentage. OMITTED.
-- [AL] - late_fee_grace_days: Alabama URLTA does NOT mandate a grace period before a late fee may apply. OMITTED.
