-- [LA] Louisiana has NO single uniform residential landlord-tenant act. Residential tenancies are governed by the Civil Code's lease title (Title IX, "Of Lease," arts. 2668-2729) plus the Civil Code Ancillaries security-deposit statute (La. R.S. 9:3251-3254). The same Title IX lease provisions govern apartments, single-family homes, mobile/manufactured homes, RV/trailer lots, and commercial leases alike.
-- [LA] NO SEPARATE MOBILE-HOME-PARK OR RV-PARK RESIDENCY ACT EXISTS. Mobile-home and manufactured-housing tenancies fall under the same general Civil Code lease law; the only mobile-home-specific statute is R.S. 9:3259.1, which merely requires the lessor to notify a secured party when lot rent is 60+ days past due. RV/trailer lots are likewise covered by the general lease law (mapped to the residential act as rv_spot for long-term tenancies). The deposit statute R.S. 9:3251 applies only to 'residential or dwelling premises,' so it does not reach commercial leases.
-- [LA] PROVISIONS DELIBERATELY OMITTED (no statutory value exists - do not invent):
-- [LA] - entry_notice_hours: Louisiana has NO landlord-entry statute. There is no statutory advance-notice requirement to enter a dwelling; the only protection is the general 'peaceful possession' obligation in Civil Code art. 2682, with no numeric notice period.
-- [LA] - deposit_max_months: Louisiana statute places NO cap on security deposit amount. R.S. 9:3251-3254 regulate return and itemization only, not maximum amount.
-- [LA] - late_fee_max_pct: NO statutory cap on late fees. Late fees are governed by general contract/stipulated-damages principles (must be a reasonable estimate of damages), with no statutory percentage limit.
-- [LA] - late_fee_grace_days: NO statutory grace period before a late fee may apply. Grace, if any, is purely a matter of the lease agreement.
-- [LA] Self-storage is carved out into its own act (Self-Service Storage Facility Act, R.S. 9:4751 et seq.); R.S. 9:4756 expressly states no lessee shall use a self-service storage facility for residential purposes, so it is not a residential tenancy regime - it is a lien/disposition statute and contains none of the six residential provisions.
-- [LA] Official source site: Louisiana State Legislature (legis.la.gov). Deposit statute R.S. 9:3251 page = Law.aspx?d=107468. Civil Code art. 2728 (notice of termination; timing) page = Law.aspx?d=109792. Civil Code art. 2668 (lease defined, entry point to Title IX) = Law.aspx?d=109729.
