-- [KY] Source of truth: official Kentucky legislature site apps.legislature.ky.gov (statute pages serve as PDFs; text quoted verbatim from them).
-- [KY] ACT STRUCTURE. Kentucky residential landlord-tenant law lives entirely in KRS Chapter 383, which is split in two:
-- [KY] - URLTA (KRS 383.500-383.715): the modern residential act with deposit/access/termination rules. CRITICAL CAVEAT: Kentucky is a local-option URLTA state. The URLTA only legally applies in cities/counties that formally adopted it (Louisville/Jefferson Co., Lexington/Fayette Co., Covington, and ~16 other jurisdictions). Statewide it is not in force. The provisions returned below are URLTA sections and apply only in adopting jurisdictions.
-- [KY] - General provisions (KRS 383.005-383.285, "Rental of property / Forcible entry and detainer"): statewide baseline governing leases, eviction (forcible detainer), tenancy-at-will termination. Governs commercial tenancies and residential tenancies in non-URLTA jurisdictions. I listed this as a second act (actKey general_rental_fed) because it is the controlling law for commercial and for the majority of KY counties; it does NOT contain deposit caps, entry-notice, or late-fee rules.
-- [KY] UNIT TYPES.
-- [KY] - mobile_home / rv_spot: Kentucky has NO dedicated mobile-home-park lot-tenancy lease act (unlike many states). Manufactured/mobile homes used as a dwelling fall under URLTA (383.545 'dwelling unit' definition) where adopted. The only state statute that specifically names mobile home parks AND RV parks is KRS Chapter 219 (Cabinet for Health and Family Services) - but it is public-health LICENSING/permitting/sanitation regulation, NOT landlord-tenant lease terms. There is no statutory entry-notice / deposit / late-fee / notice-to-vacate rule for RV spots specifically.
-- [KY] - storage (self-storage): NOT governed by KRS 383 or 219. No self-storage facility act surfaced in this research; omitted from acts.
-- [KY] - commercial: no separate commercial landlord-tenant act; governed by the general KRS 383 provisions + lease contract + common law.
-- [KY] PROVISIONS DELIBERATELY OMITTED (statute specifies NO value - did not invent):
-- [KY] - deposit_max_months: KRS 383.580 imposes NO cap on security deposit amount. Omitted.
-- [KY] - deposit_return_days: KRS 383.580 has NO clean 'return within X days' mandate. It requires a separate escrow account, a move-in and move-out itemized damage listing, and (subsection 7) says if a refund is due the landlord notifies the tenant's last known address and may retain unclaimed funds only after 60 days with no response. The widely-cited '30/60 day' figures are misreadings: the 30 days (subsection 6) is when a landlord MAY pull a deposit to cover unpaid last-month rent, and the 60 days (subsection 7) is the no-response window before the landlord may KEEP an unclaimed refund - neither is a deadline to RETURN the deposit. Because the statute sets no affirmative return deadline, I omitted this provision rather than misrepresent a number.
-- [KY] - late_fee_max_pct: NO statutory cap on late fees anywhere in KRS 383. Omitted.
-- [KY] - late_fee_grace_days: NO statutory grace period before a late fee may apply. Omitted. (Note: KRS 383.660 gives a tenant a 7-day cure window after a notice of nonpayment before the landlord can terminate for nonpayment, but that is an eviction-cure period, not a late-fee grace period.)
-- [KY] Key statute IDs on the official site for reuse: deposit=35733, access/entry=35740, periodic-tenancy/notice=35756, maintenance=35736, definitions=35726, tenant-nonpayment cure=35749. Chapter 219 id used (39149) was inferred for the official chapter URL and should be spot-verified before display; the 383 chapter URL (id=39159) is confirmed.
