-- [OR] Source: official Oregon Legislature site (https://www.oregonlegislature.gov/bills_laws/ors/ors090.html); verbatim quotes cross-verified against the public.law ORS mirror (oregon.public.law) for exact subsection text not surfaced in the truncated .gov page fetch.
-- [OR] ACTS: Oregon consolidates nearly all residential tenancy types into ONE act — ORS Chapter 90, the Residential Landlord and Tenant Act. There is no separate mobile-home-park or RV-park landlord-tenant act. Chapter 90 covers apartments and standard residential dwellings (ORS 90.100–90.493) AND manufactured-dwelling-park / floating-home / RV-space tenancies via dedicated subdivisions (ORS 90.505–90.850 for facility/park tenancies; recreational-vehicle space tenancies in a park are treated under the same chapter). Therefore residential, single_family, mobile_home, and rv_spot all map to Chapter 90. ORS Chapter 446 is a SEPARATE, non-landlord-tenant statute governing the physical facility — park licensing, sanitation, building/plumbing standards — not the rental relationship; included only as the secondary mobile_home reference. Chapter 90 explicitly excludes commercial and self-storage tenancies (it applies only to "dwelling units"), so no act was returned for commercial or storage unit types.
-- [OR] PROVISIONS — important nuances:
-- [OR] - deposit_max_months: OMITTED. Oregon ORS 90.300 imposes NO statutory cap on the security deposit amount (no months-of-rent limit). Do not invent one.
-- [OR] - late_fee_max_pct: Oregon's late-fee statute (ORS 90.260) authorizes THREE methods and the percentage cap depends on method. (a) A reasonable flat amount once per period — NO fixed percentage cap, only "reasonable." (b) A per-day charge that "may not exceed six percent" of the reasonable flat amount — this is the 6% value recorded. (c) Alternatively, "Five percent of the periodic rent payment amount, charged once for each succeeding five-day period." So 6% is the per-day cap (relative to the flat amount, not relative to rent), and 5% is the per-five-day-period cap relative to rent. The single recorded value (6%, unit percent_per_day) reflects the explicit statutory per-day ceiling; consumers should note the 5%-per-5-day alternative and the uncapped "reasonable flat" method.
-- [OR] - late_fee_grace_days: 4 days. A late charge may not be imposed unless rent is "not received by the fourth day"; per-day/period charges begin "on the fifth day." So 4 full days of grace.
-- [OR] - notice_to_vacate_days: 30 days recorded as the statutory minimum for ending a month-to-month tenancy. ORS 90.427(3)(a) sets the tenant's floor at "not less than 30 days." A landlord may also terminate on 30 days during the first year of occupancy (90.427(3)(b)); AFTER the first year a landlord generally needs 90 days plus a qualifying/for-cause reason (90.427(5)), and many Oregon localities (e.g., Portland) add relocation-assistance overlays. 30 days is the bare statutory minimum-notice value for a month-to-month tenancy.
