-- [OK] Verified verbatim against the official Oklahoma Senate statute PDF (oksenate.gov, Title 41, 2022 compilation; sections unchanged through 2025). OSCN (oscn.net) and the Senate PDF are the official OK sources; both block automated fetch (CAPTCHA / binary PDF), so I downloaded the Senate PDF and extracted text directly to confirm every quote.
-- [OK] ACTS: Oklahoma has ONE residential landlord-tenant act (Title 41, §§101-136). There is NO separate Manufactured Home Park / Mobile Home Park Act in Oklahoma. Mobile/manufactured home lots are folded into the main act: §41-102(3) defines 'Dwelling unit' as 'a structure... used as a home, residence or sleeping place... and includes any site, space or lot leased to the owner or resident of a manufactured or mobile home,' and §41-102(5) extends 'Landlord' to a 'manufactured or mobile home site, space or lot.' (Some third-party sites erroneously cite a non-existent OK '§§201-231 Manufactured Home Park Act' — §41-201 is actually about felony-conviction lease terms for LIHTC properties. Confirmed against the official text.)
-- [OK] RV: No RV-specific statute exists. Long-term RV-spot residency plausibly falls under the residential act's 'dwelling unit / sleeping place / site, space or lot' language, so I listed rv_spot under the residential act. CAVEAT: this is an interpretive stretch, not an explicit RV reference; nightly/transient RV occupancy is EXCLUDED by §41-104(4) ('Transient occupancy in a hotel, motel or other similar lodging'). Treat residential-act coverage of rv_spot as long-term-only and not statutorily named.
-- [OK] COMMERCIAL/STORAGE: Oklahoma has no comprehensive commercial landlord-tenant act; commercial leases are governed by contract and common law. Title 41 §§51-52 are the only commercial-adjacent statutory provisions — they govern disposition of personal property abandoned on 'nonresidential rental property' (the storage/lien-style remedy), which is why commercial+storage are mapped there. This is NOT a full commercial act.
-- [OK] OMITTED PROVISIONS (statute is silent — did NOT invent values):
-- [OK] - deposit_max_months: §41-115 imposes escrow and return-timing rules but sets NO cap on the deposit amount.
-- [OK] - late_fee_max_pct: The Act contains no late-fee cap. Late fees in OK are governed by general contract law (Title 15 §§213/215 liquidated-damages vs. penalty doctrine, per Sun Ridge Investors v. Parker, 1998 OK 22), NOT by Title 41 — so it does not belong as a Title 41 provision value.
-- [OK] - late_fee_grace_days: The Act mandates no grace period before a late fee may apply. (Separately, §41-131 gives a 5-day cure window after written demand before a landlord may TERMINATE for nonpayment, but that is an eviction-cure period, not a late-fee grace period, so it is not mapped to late_fee_grace_days.)
--
-- [CT] SCOPE: Connecticut's residential framework spans three chapters of Title 47a, all part of the same statutory scheme: Ch. 830 (core landlord-tenant rights/duties, including entry § 47a-16 and late charges § 47a-15a), Ch. 831 (security deposits § 47a-21), and Ch. 832 (summary process / notice to quit § 47a-23). I grouped them under one 'residential' act because the provisions requested are distributed across them and § 47a-2 cross-references them as a unit.
-- [CT] ENTRY NOTICE OMITTED (intentional, not missed): § 47a-16(c) requires only that the landlord 'give the tenant reasonable written or oral notice of his intent to enter' — NO fixed number of hours is specified in the statute. Per instructions I did not invent a number.
-- [CT] UNIT TYPE COVERAGE:
-- [CT] - apartment / single_family: governed by Ch. 830/831/832 (dwelling units).
-- [CT] - mobile_home: split. Under § 47a-2(b), renting the SPACE/LOT to a resident who OWNS the mobile home is governed by Ch. 412 (NOT Ch. 830). Renting a mobile home + premises to a non-owner is governed by Ch. 830. Ch. 831 (deposits), 832 (summary process), 833, 834 apply to ALL park residents including home owners, except as Ch. 412 provides otherwise. I listed mobile_home under both acts to reflect this.
-- [CT] - rv_spot: NO dedicated Connecticut act. Ch. 412's 'mobile manufactured home' definition (§ 21-64(1)) requires a unit 'designed for long-term occupancy ... placed on rigid supports at the site where it is to be occupied as a residence' — this excludes recreational vehicles/travel trailers. RV/transient occupancy is also excluded from Ch. 830 protections via § 47a-2(a)(4) (transient hotel/motel/'similar lodging' under 30 days). So I did NOT assign rv_spot to either act — it is statutorily unaddressed in CT.
-- [CT] - commercial: largely EXCLUDED from the protective residential provisions. Ch. 830/831 'were passed to aid residential apartment dwellers and do not apply to commercial leases.' § 47a-21(c) case law (74 CA 460) confirms the deposit law 'relates only to residential real property and ... is inapplicable to case concerning commercial property.' Commercial appears only in summary-process mechanics (§ 47a-23(a)(1)(E)). No commercial-specific act exists; omitted from acts list.
-- [CT] - storage: no Connecticut landlord-tenant act covers self-storage under Title 47a; omitted.
-- [CT] DEPOSIT: § 47a-21(b)(2) sets a LOWER cap of ONE month's rent for tenants 62+. I reported the standard 2-month cap as the deposit_max_months value. The 21-day return was reduced from 30 days by P.A. 23-207 (effective 2023) per the statute's history note.
-- [CT] LATE FEE: the § 47a-15a(b) cap is the LESSER of ($5/day up to $50) OR (5% of delinquent rent). I encoded the 5% component as late_fee_max_pct since that is the percent-of-rent ceiling; note the absolute $50 / $5-per-day cap may bind first on lower rents. Late charges also require a valid written agreement in the lease (§ 47a-4a). This cap was added by P.A. 23-207 (2023).
-- [CT] NOTICE TO VACATE: Connecticut does NOT use a 30-day notice to end a month-to-month tenancy. Termination runs through the statutory notice to quit (§ 47a-23), which requires 'at least three days' before termination (reduced from five days by P.A. 97-231). For a one-week tenancy the rent grace period is 4 days (§ 47a-15a(a)). All values verified against official cga.ct.gov chapter text (fetched 2026-06-11).
